### 2.6. Core loop {#2.6.-core-loop}

There are the class cards that determine what each player is. This stays in their hand for the whole time. The turns follow this sequence:

1. Player can use their class related abilities  
2. Player can play any other potion or treasure card from their hand  
3. Players draw a card from the shared deck.  
   1. If it’s a trap, the player must reveal the trap card and the effects are activated unless the player has an ability that blocks it  
   2. If it is any other card, the player does not reveal it and adds it to their hand  
4. Next player starts their turn

### 2.7. Look & Feel {#2.7.-look-&-feel}

Comedic cartoon aesthetic. The tone is a parody of fantasy games and the art in the cards exemplifies this. The game is supposed to be chaotic and fast. The feel of the game is exaggerated and supposed to be funny.

## 3\. Gameplay {#3.-gameplay}

### 3.1. Objectives {#3.1.-objectives}

The main objective for  players is to have the most amount of gold left when the game ends. To achieve this they must stay alive long enough in order to collect more gold from the deck. They have to manage their abilities and HP. They must also choose when to redirect cards and traps to others via the treasure cards.

### 3.2. Play flow {#3.2.-play-flow}

A typical game session lasts about 10 minutes. Players are able to accumulate resources faster in the early game, but as the traps end up getting reshuffled it becomes more likely to hit a trap in the late game. The last man standing gets a bonus of 3 gold. Because of the nature of the game, some players may die early which is why keeping the game as quick rounds means that they won’t stay spectators for long

## 4\. Mechanics {#4.-mechanics}

### 4.1. Rules {#4.1.-rules}

Each player selects a class before the game starts. Class cards are then given to players and they stay in their hand.  
The deck is shuffled and then placed face down.  
Trap cards must be revealed   
A player dies when their hp reaches zero  
Gold earning is locked once the player is dead  
If there is a tie in gold, the player that survived longer wins

### 4.2. Economy {#4.2.-economy}

The economy depends on which character you play. For the knight, repairing armor costs gold so repairing the armor is a meaningful decision that must be made. The mage uses mana so their economy relies on them surviving for long enough to build it up, finally the thief does not have an economy, instead they must outlast other players to steal from them.

